{"title_page": "Rebecca Bardoux", "text_new": "{{short description|American pornographic actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox adult biography\n| name            = Rebecca Bardoux\n| image           = Rebecca_bardoux.jpg\n| caption         = Bardoux at the 1995 [[AVN Awards]]\n| birth_name      = \n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1963|08|18}}<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux IAFD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iafd.com/person.rme/perfid=RBardoux/gender=female|title=Rebecca Bardoux|accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref>\n| birth_place     = [[Erie, Pennsylvania]], United States<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux IAFD\" />\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| spouse          = \n| height          = {{height|ft=5|in=6}}<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux IAFD\" />\n| weight          = {{convert|110|lb|kg}}<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux IAFD\" />\n| alias           = Rebecca Bandoux, Rebecca Bordeaux, Rebecca Bordoux, Rebecca Bardeaux, Rebecca Bardot,<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux IAFD\" /> Rebecca Bardaux, Rebecca Bardeoux, Rebecca Bardo, Rebecca Bardous<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux AFDB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.adultfilmdatabase.com/actor/rebecca-bardoux-220/|title=Rebecca Bardoux|accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref>\n| number_of_films = 298 {{small|(per [[Internet Adult Film Database|IAFD]] as of May 2016)}}<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux IAFD\" />\n| website         = {{url|http://www.rebeccabardouxonline.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Rebecca Bardoux''' (born August 18, 1963) is an [[Americans|America]]n [[pornographic film actor|pornographic actress]].<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux IAFD\" /> She made her debut in the [[adult film industry]] in 1992 at age 29.<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux IAFD\" />\n\n==Career==\n[[Sean Michaels (pornographic actor)|Sean Michaels]] introduced Bardoux to various industry people, took her on set, and shot her first scene.<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux: The Classiest Woman in Porn interview\">{{cite web|url=http://pornlifemagazine.com/issue/november-2012/article/rebecca-bardoux|title=Rebecca Bardoux: The Classiest Woman in Porn|accessdate= 2012-09-15|date= 2012-09-15}}</ref>\n\nBardoux co-starred in the AVN Best Film for 1992 ''Face Dance'', directed by [[John Stagliano]]. She later went on to be nominated for Best Supporting Actress in a Film for her performance in 2003's ''Heartbreaker'' for [[Vivid Entertainment]], directed by [[Paul Thomas (pornographic actor)|Paul Thomas]].\n\nIn 2013 Bardoux entered [[stand-up comedy]].<ref name=2013Comedy>{{cite web|last1=Staff|title=Rebecca Bardoux Premieres Standup Comedy Act|url=http://business.avn.com/company-news/Rebecca-Bardoux-Premieres-Standup-Comedy-Act-507942.html|website=AVN.com|publisher=Adult Video News|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> Since then she has performed at [[The Comedy Store]] in Hollywood as well as other comedy venues in Los Angeles and Las Vegas.<ref name=2015ComedySaphire>{{cite web|title=AVN and Sapphire Comedy Hour Present \u201cCarnal Comedy\u201d on January 22, 2015 at Sapphire, \u201cWorld\u2019s Largest Gentlemen\u2019s Club\u201d in Las Vegas|url=http://www.vegasnews.com/126302/avn-and-sapphire-comedy-hour-present-carnal-comedy-on-january-22-2015-at-sapphire-worlds-largest-gentlemens-club-in-las-vegas.html|website=vagasnews.com|publisher=Bryan Eggers|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Advocacy===\nBardoux has spoken out against [[Measure B]], legislation that requires [[adult film]] workers to use condoms during the production of scenes. In October 2012, just prior to voting on the Measure, she was a guest speaker on Los Angeles [[public radio]] station [[KCRW]].<ref name=2012KCRWPanel>{{cite web|last1=Simon|first1=Scott|title=Measure B: Enforcing the Use of Condoms in Pornography|url=http://www.kcrw.com/news-culture/shows/which-way-la/measure-b-enforcing-the-use-of-condoms-in-pornography#seg-should-la-county-require-condoms-for-porn|website=www.kcrw.com|publisher=KCRW Public Radio|accessdate=20 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n*2007 [[AVN Hall of Fame]]<ref>{{cite magazine|url= http://business.avn.com/articles/video/2007-AVN-Award-Winners-Announced-29596.html|title= 2007 AVN Award Winners Announced|accessdate= 2014-06-06|date= 2007-01-14|magazine= [[AVN (magazine)|AVN]]}}</ref>\n*2011 NightMoves Hall of Fame<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nightmovesusa.com/awards-show/past-winner-history.html |title=Past Winner History |accessdate=2014-06-06 |publisher=NightMoves |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219210715/http://nightmovesusa.com/awards-show/past-winner-history.html |archivedate=December 19, 2013 }}</ref>\n*2014 [[XRCO Hall of Fame]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.xbiz.com/news/174997|title= XRCO Announces 2014 Hall of Fame Inductees|accessdate= 2014-06-06|author= John Sanford|date= 2014-02-18|publisher= [[XBIZ]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.rebeccabardouxonline.com/rebecca_bardoux_bio.html Rebecca Bardoux Biography at Official Site]\n* {{IMDb name|0054338|Rebecca Bardoux}}\n* {{iafd name|id=RBardoux|gender=female|name=Rebecca Bardoux}}\n* {{afdb name|id=220|gender=female|name=Rebecca Bardoux}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bardoux, Rebecca}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:American pornographic film actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actors from Erie, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Pornographic film actors from Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American pornographic actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox adult biography\n| name            = Rebecca Bardoux\n| image           = Rebecca_bardoux.jpg\n| caption         = Bardoux at the 1995 [[AVN Awards]]\n| birth_name      = \n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1963|08|18}}<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux IAFD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iafd.com/person.rme/perfid=RBardoux/gender=female|title=Rebecca Bardoux|accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref>\n| birth_place     = [[Erie, Pennsylvania]], United States<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux IAFD\" />\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| spouse          = \n| height          = {{height|ft=5|in=6}}<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux IAFD\" />\n| weight          = {{convert|110|lb|kg}}<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux IAFD\" />\n| alias           = Rebecca Bandoux, Rebecca Bordeaux, Rebecca Bordoux, Rebecca Bardeaux, Rebecca Bardot,<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux IAFD\" /> Rebecca Bardaux, Rebecca Bardeoux, Rebecca Bardo, Rebecca Bardous<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux AFDB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.adultfilmdatabase.com/actor/rebecca-bardoux-220/|title=Rebecca Bardoux|accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref>\n| number_of_films = 298 {{small|(per [[Internet Adult Film Database|IAFD]] as of May 2016)}}<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux IAFD\" />\n| website         = {{url|http://www.rebeccabardouxonline.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Rebecca Bardoux''' (born August 18, 1963) is an [[Americans|America]]n [[pornographic film actor|pornographic actress]].<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux IAFD\" /> She made her debut in the [[adult film industry]] in 1992 at age 29.<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux IAFD\" />\n\n==Career==\n[[Sean Michaels (pornographic actor)|Sean Michaels]] introduced Bardoux to various industry people, took her on set, and shot her first scene.<ref name=\"Rebecca Bardoux: The Classiest Woman in Porn interview\">{{cite web|url=http://pornlifemagazine.com/issue/november-2012/article/rebecca-bardoux|title=Rebecca Bardoux: The Classiest Woman in Porn|accessdate= 2012-09-15|date= 2012-09-15}}</ref>\n\nBardoux co-starred in the AVN Best Film for 1992 ''Face Dance'', directed by [[John Stagliano]]. She later went on to be nominated for Best Supporting Actress in a Film for her performance in 2003\u2018s ''Heartbreaker'' for [[Vivid Entertainment]], directed by [[Paul Thomas (pornographic actor)|Paul Thomas]].\n\nIn 2013 Bardoux entered [[stand-up comedy]].<ref name=2013Comedy>{{cite web|last1=Staff|title=Rebecca Bardoux Premieres Standup Comedy Act|url=http://business.avn.com/company-news/Rebecca-Bardoux-Premieres-Standup-Comedy-Act-507942.html|website=AVN.com|publisher=Adult Video News|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> Since then she has performed at [[The Comedy Store]] in Hollywood as well as other comedy venues in Los Angeles and Las Vegas.<ref name=2015ComedySaphire>{{cite web|title=AVN and Sapphire Comedy Hour Present \u201cCarnal Comedy\u201d on January 22, 2015 at Sapphire, \u201cWorld\u2019s Largest Gentlemen\u2019s Club\u201d in Las Vegas|url=http://www.vegasnews.com/126302/avn-and-sapphire-comedy-hour-present-carnal-comedy-on-january-22-2015-at-sapphire-worlds-largest-gentlemens-club-in-las-vegas.html|website=vagasnews.com|publisher=Bryan Eggers|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Advocacy===\nBardoux has spoken out against [[Measure B]], legislation that requires [[adult film]] workers to use condoms during the production of scenes. In October 2012, just prior to voting on the Measure, she was a guest speaker on Los Angeles [[public radio]] station [[KCRW]].<ref name=2012KCRWPanel>{{cite web|last1=Simon|first1=Scott|title=Measure B: Enforcing the Use of Condoms in Pornography|url=http://www.kcrw.com/news-culture/shows/which-way-la/measure-b-enforcing-the-use-of-condoms-in-pornography#seg-should-la-county-require-condoms-for-porn|website=www.kcrw.com|publisher=KCRW Public Radio|accessdate=20 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n*2007 [[AVN Hall of Fame]]<ref>{{cite magazine|url= http://business.avn.com/articles/video/2007-AVN-Award-Winners-Announced-29596.html|title= 2007 AVN Award Winners Announced|accessdate= 2014-06-06|date= 2007-01-14|magazine= [[AVN (magazine)|AVN]]}}</ref>\n*2011 NightMoves Hall of Fame<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nightmovesusa.com/awards-show/past-winner-history.html |title=Past Winner History |accessdate=2014-06-06 |publisher=NightMoves |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219210715/http://nightmovesusa.com/awards-show/past-winner-history.html |archivedate=December 19, 2013 }}</ref>\n*2014 [[XRCO Hall of Fame]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.xbiz.com/news/174997|title= XRCO Announces 2014 Hall of Fame Inductees|accessdate= 2014-06-06|author= John Sanford|date= 2014-02-18|publisher= [[XBIZ]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.rebeccabardouxonline.com/rebecca_bardoux_bio.html Rebecca Bardoux Biography at Official Site]\n* {{IMDb name|0054338|Rebecca Bardoux}}\n* {{iafd name|id=RBardoux|gender=female|name=Rebecca Bardoux}}\n* {{afdb name|id=220|gender=female|name=Rebecca Bardoux}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bardoux, Rebecca}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:American pornographic film actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actors from Erie, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Pornographic film actors from Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2018s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rebecca_Bardoux"}
{"title_page": "Scott O'Hara", "text_new": "{{Infobox adult biography\n|name = Scott O'Hara\n|image = Scott OHara Advocate Men May 1985.jpg\n|image_size = 220px\n|caption = Scott O'Hara, circa 1984\n|birth_name = John Robert Scott\n|birth_date = {{birth date|mf=yes|1961|10|16}}\n|birth_place = [[Grants Pass, Oregon]], U.S.\n|spouse =\n|death_date = {{Death date and age|mf=yes|1998|02|18|1961|10|16}}\n|death_place = [[San Francisco, California]], U.S.\n|height = \n|weight =\n|alias = Spunk\n|films =\n|number of films =\n|website =\n}}\n\n'''Scott O'Hara''' (October 16, 1961 \u2013 February 18, 1998) was an American pornographic performer, author, poet, editor and publisher.  He rose to prominence during the mid-1980s for his work in such gay adult films as ''Winner Takes All'', ''Below The Belt'' and ''In Your Wildest Dreams''. O'Hara wrote four books: ''SeXplorers: The Guide to Doing It on the Road'', ''Do It Yourself Piston Polishing (for Non-Mechanics)'', ''Autopornography: A Memoir of Life in the Lust Lane'', and ''Rarely Pure and Never Simple: Selected Essays of Scott O'Hara'', and edited and published the quarterly men's sex journal ''[[Steam (gay magazine)|Steam]]'' and the cultural magazine ''Wilde''.\n\n==Acting career==\nO'Hara was born '''John Robert Scott''' on October 16, 1961 in [[Grants Pass, Oregon]], one of seven children of Robert Hogue Scott and Martha Jane (n\u00e9e Farwell) Scott. While the family lived modestly on the family farm, there was inherited wealth, and for much of his life Scott was supported by a trust fund. Scott was known professionally as \"Scott O'Hara\" or \"Spunk\"<ref name=\"Advocate Men\">{{citation|title='Spunk'. The name reverberates, the body arrests.|date=May 1985|work=Advocate Men}}</ref> and used his professional name throughout his adult life.  In an essay titled \"A Dick by Any Other Name\", O'Hara wrote: \"I knew from an early age that I was a changeling. I spent the next eighteen years looking for my real name, and since I found it I have not pretended to be anyone else.\"<ref name=\"Rarely Pure and never simple\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QKlE8exUdeMC&pg=PA5&lpg=PA5&dq=|title=A Dick by Any Other Name|author=Scott O'Hara|work=Rarely pure and never simple|publisher=Psychology Press. \u00a91999|isbn=9780789005731|year=1999}}</ref>\n\nHe first came to prominence when he was awarded the title \"The Man With The Biggest Dick in San Francisco\" in a contest in the early 1980s. That title became his trademark for the rest of his porn and professional career. Published measurement of his penis varies from 9.5 to 11&nbsp;inches. From 1983\u201388, he appeared in over twenty gay and bisexual-themed adult films and videos, several of which demonstrate his rare ability of [[autofellatio|auto-fellatio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gayeroticvideoindex.com/V/4/1404.html|title=Head Over Heels|date=1988|work=All Worlds Video}}</ref>  In addition to his work in adult films, O'Hara starred in ''Making Porn'', a play by [[Ronnie Larsen]] based on conversations by Larsen with Scott O'Hara. He described his work in porn as \"a sheer delight from the word go\".<ref name=\"Autopornography-p.90\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-H-ZS4J5oiAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Autopornography:+A+Memoir+of+Life+in+the+Lust+Lane#v=onepage&q=bisexual&f=false|title=Autopornography: A Memoir of Life in the Lust Lane|author=Scott O'Hara|date=1997|publisher=Haworth Press|isbn=9780789001443}}, p. 90.</ref>\n\n==Writing career==\nAfter he contracted HIV, offers to appear in porn ended. In 1991 he moved to [[Cazenovia, Wisconsin]] and started a new career as an author. He edited and published from 1993 to 1995 the quarterly men's journal ''Steam'', \"the intellectual review of public sex\", intended to facilitate [[Cruising for sex|cruising]]. According to its first issue, ''Steam'' focused on \"public and semi-public sex. Our purpose is to provide a sex-positive forum for subjects considered taboo by other mags. We are aware that many activities mentioned in these pages are illegal in many parts of the world, and we do not advocate unlawful activity\". In an advertisement in Volume 2, No. 1, he further stated that the publication was \"all about sex - all kinds of sex, but especially public, publicly-disapproved, exciting sex\". Articles often featured rest room, park, and other risky sexual encounters, and every issue contained tips on cruising spots (public places to meet men for sex), with notes on their safety or lack of same.<ref>Wisconsin GLBT History Project, http://www.mkelgbthist.org/media/print/steam.htm, consulted 10-29-2014.</ref>\n\nReturning to San Francisco in 1995, he published five issues of the short-lived cultural magazine ''Wilde''; he also contributed to a number of other publications. O'Hara wrote the four books  mentioned above. As a playwright, he contributed to the musical, ''Ex-Lovers'', which had a successful run at the [[Theatre Rhinoceros]] in San Francisco.<ref name=\"POZ\">{{cite web|url=http://www.poz.com/articles/228_7134.shtml|title=Full of Spunk|author=Adam Gillitt|date=June 1998|accessdate=January 14, 2014|work=Poz Magazine}}</ref>\n\nUpon his death, he left his personal papers (consisting of 39 boxes of journals, correspondence, notes, and manuscripts) to the [[John Hay Library]] of [[Brown University]]. The archives of the [[GLBT Historical Society]] in San Francisco preserve a collection of O'Hara's performance costumes and other memorabilia.<ref>Scott O'Hara Artifacts (collection no. 1998-19); see the entry in the [http://www.glbthistory.org/research online catalog of the society].</ref> The sibling to whom he had been closest was the lesbian activist and poet Claudia (Ann) Scott<ref>https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/37308382</ref><ref>''Sinister Wisdom'', No13 http://www.sinisterwisdom.org/sites/default/files/Sinister%20Wisdom%2013.pdf</ref> who left him the poem ''For My Youngest Brother''.<ref>''Lesbian Writer: Collected Work Of Claudia Scott'', Naiad Press 1981</ref>\n\n==Sexuality==\nO'Hara identified as gay.<ref name=\"Autopornography-p.114\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-H-ZS4J5oiAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Autopornography:+A+Memoir+of+Life+in+the+Lust+Lane#v=onepage&q=bisexual&f=false|title=Autopornography: A Memoir of Life in the Lust Lane|author=Scott O'Hara|date=1997|publisher=Haworth Press|isbn=9780789001443}}, p. 114</ref> He said he was \"obsessed with anything sexual\" as young as eleven,<ref name=\"Autopornography-p.70\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-H-ZS4J5oiAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Autopornography:+A+Memoir+of+Life+in+the+Lust+Lane#v=onepage&q=bisexual&f=false|title=Autopornography: A Memoir of Life in the Lust Lane|author=Scott O'Hara|date=1997|publisher=Haworth Press|isbn=9780789001443}}, p. 70</ref> and that his first sex with another man took place when he was fifteen, when he seduced, or perhaps raped (the word is his), a twenty-eight-year-old.<ref name=\"Autopornography-p.71\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-H-ZS4J5oiAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Autopornography:+A+Memoir+of+Life+in+the+Lust+Lane#v=onepage&q=bisexual&f=false|title=Autopornography: A Memoir of Life in the Lust Lane|author=Scott O'Hara|date=1997|publisher=Haworth Press|isbn=9780789001443}}, p. 71</ref> He called [[monogamy]] \"unnatural,\" and stated that \"having our [gay men's] mouth full of dick has been a political statement like no other\".<ref>\"Talking with My Mouth Full\", p. 81.</ref> He frequented [[gay bathhouses]] and other men's sex clubs, and much enjoyed sex in public parks. Until his HIV infection, he had \"a different man every night, or nearly\".<ref>''Autopornography'', p. 120.</ref>\n\nO'Hara was a proponent of [[barebacking]], praising the freedom from fear of risk it gave him. This attracted criticism both during his life, and following his death.<ref>e.g. See discussion between the notable authors Ricketts & Halsall, ''Gaynet List Serve'', Feb 1998: https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/bit.listserv.gaynet/U8GN3aqUGOk</ref> He called his HIV infection, which he believed he contracted in 1981, \"an undeniable blessing\",<ref name=\"Autopornography, p. 129\">''Autopornography'', p. 129</ref> and \"admired..tremendously\" two people who \"consciously made the decision to seroconvert\" (to contract HIV; see [[bugchasing]]).<ref name=\"Autopornography, p. 129\"/><ref>\"Talking with My Mouth Full\", p. 84.</ref> He had \"HIV+\" tattooed on his bicep in 1994, then tore the sleeves off many of his shirts so it would be visible.<ref>''Autopornography'', p. 128.?</ref><ref>[[David M. Halperin]], ''What Do Gay Men Want?'' pp. 88-89, University of Michigan Press, 2007</ref> Once he had progressed to AIDS, he talked about it \"at every available opportunity\".<ref>\"Talking with My Mouth Full\", p. 83.</ref> He wrote in detail about his treatment for lymphoma and the pain he endured.<ref>''Out On A Lymphoma'', ''POZ'', June 1998 http://www.poz.com/articles/228_1623.shtml</ref>\n\nO'Hara did not have, and did not want, a long-term relationship. He said that there were six times in his life when he was in love, deeply and thoroughly, for a period of a month or more.<ref>''Autopornography'', p. 159.</ref> \"The concept of 'Lover' (or 'Spouse', or 'Partner', or whatever) is basically, intrinsically antithetical to what my Philosophy of Life holds up as the ideal\".<ref>''Autopornography'', p. 173.</ref>\n\nO'Hara acted in multiple [[Bisexual pornography|bisexual films]] throughout his life, but did not identify as bisexual. However, he listed ''Switch Hitters 2'' as one of his favorite films, partly because he got to experience the novelty of sex with a woman, something he'd always wanted to do. He claimed to enjoy the scene and was proud of his butch appearance in the role, writing that \"in all my years of ass-pounding, I'd never once gotten into a pussy, and I felt as if this were a serious gap in my sexual education, which needed filling.\"<ref name=\"Autopornography-p.114\"/>\n\n==Death==\nHis trust fund exhausted, O'Hara spent his final years in a windowless San Francisco apartment he called \"The Cave\", surrounded by his record albums, CDs, books, and erotic art, and occupied his time gardening.<ref name=\"POZ\"/> He lived with [[HIV]] for more than 10 years and had developed [[non-Hodgkin lymphoma]] for almost five years.  He dubbed his illness \"The Death Spoor\", and died of [[AIDS]]-related complications in San Francisco on February 18, 1998, at age 36.<ref name=\"POZ\"/> He donated his collection of over 500 works of erotic art to The Tom of Finland Foundation.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldoftomoffinland.com/tomsblog/?p=4626 | title=Scott O'Hara \u2013 ToFF Lifetime Member &#124; TOM's Blog}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}} \n*''Winner Takes All'' (1982)\n*''California Blue'' (1983)\n*''Ramcharger'' (1984)\n*''Slaves for Sale 2'' (1984)\n*''The Joys of Self-Abuse'' (1985)\n*''The Other Side Of Aspen 2'' (1985)\n*''Sgt. Swann's Private Files'' (1985)\n*''Sighs'' (1985)\n*''Advocate Men Live! 1'' (1986)\n*''Below the Belt'' (1986)\n*''The Guy Next Door'' (1986)\n*''Hung and Horny'' (1986)\n*''Oversized Load'' (1986)\n*''Sex-Hunt'' (1986)\n*''Stick Shift'' (1986)\n*''In Your Wildest Dreams'' (1987)\n*''Switch Hitters 2'' (1987)\n*''Advocate Men Live! 4'' (1988)\n*''Double Standards'' (1988)\n*''Head Over Heels 1'' (1988)\n*''New Recruits'' (1988)\n*''The Sex Party'' (1992)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Publications==\n* \"How I Got AIDS. Memoirs of a Working Boy\", ''Diseased Pariah News'', No. 3, 1991, p.&nbsp;7; No. 4, 1991, pp.&nbsp;7\u20138 (pictured on p.&nbsp;2); No. 5, no date, p.&nbsp;6; No. 6, 1992, p.&nbsp;14; No. 7, 1992, p.&nbsp;29; https://web.archive.org/web/20160624103522/http://www.diseasedpariahnews.com/, retrieved 10-29-2014. \n*  ''SeXplorers: The Guide to Doing It on the Road'', San Francisco, PDA Press, 1995, {{ISBN|9780964548015}}.\n*  ''Do It Yourself Piston Polishing (for Non-Mechanics)'' (Badboy, 1996) {{ISBN|9781563334894}}.\n*  ''Autopornography: A Memoir of Life in the Lust Lane'' (New York: Haworth Press, 1997) {{ISBN|9780789001443}}.\n*  \"Out on a Lymphoma\", ''Poz'', June 1998, http://www.poz.com/articles/228_1623.shtml, retrieved 10-28-2014.\n*  ''Rarely Pure and Never Simple: Selected Essays of Scott O'Hara'' (New York: Haworth Press, 1999), {{ISBN|9780789005731}}, containing:  Do Be Fruitful, Won't You Dear? The Truth Is... A Dick by Any Other Name Making Porn: The Hangover Seeing Beauty Whaddya Like? Where There's a Wall, There's a Way GWM, 35, Horizontal, Versatile, Asleep Playing with My Mind Schloop, Spooge, Spunk: A Syntax of Sex Testament Call Me Irresponsible Better Than Sex Why Is a Beach? Ripe and Ready My Last Parasite Feeling a Little Queer Wholesome and Natural Ah, Unity Is That a Tumor on Your Tummy, or... ? The Opinionated Pervert Kilo-Mania Codeine Is God In Recovery Going Through a Phase Breaking the Rules Doubting Death Loving Life In a Former Life Rarely Pure Learning Lust Do It Yourself Candid Camera Through a Maze, Darkly Soaking In It Owning the Road Performed Consent Hot Nights in the Deep-Freeze: Porn in the Nineties In Love with My Work I Know It When I See It You May Already Be Dead ... and Never Simple Taking Photos Turned Off Slightly More Than Two Cents' Worth Gay Life Ends at 40 Billiard Ball An Acquired Taste Learning to Love the Bomb No, Really, I Mean It More Reasons Why I Don't Want a Lover Up in Lights Handcuffed Together Love and the Challenger Disaster Unlimited Sex Only.\n*   \"Talking with My Mouth Full\", in ''Policing public sex : queer politics and the future of AIDS activism'', ed. Ephen Glenn Colter ''et al'', Boston, South End Press, 1999, {{ISBN|089608549X}}, pp.&nbsp;81\u201386. Limited preview available at https://www.amazon.com/Policing-Public-Sex-Politics-Activism/dp/089608549X/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1414505424&sr=1-1.\n\n== See also==\n*[[List of male performers in gay porn films]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://josiah.brown.edu/record=b3650724~S7 Scott O'Hara Papers, 1979-1998] at the Brown University Library.\n* [http://www.queerculturalcenter.org/Pages/Keehnen/OHara.html 1997 Scott O'Hara Interview] by Owen Keehnen at the Queer Cultural Center.\n* [http://www.poz.com/articles/257_1842.shtml \"Sex Positive\"] (article about O'Hara in June, 1995, issue of ''POZ'').\n* [http://www.poz.com/articles/228_7134.shtml \"Full of Spunk. The biggest sex radical of all is gone\"] (obituary for O'Hara in June, 1998, issue of ''POZ'').\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060612025348/http://www.scottohara.com/ Scott O'Hara Tribute Site].\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ohara, Scott}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:1998 deaths]]\n[[Category:American actors in gay pornographic films]]\n[[Category:AIDS-related deaths in California]]\n[[Category:American male pornographic film actors]]\n[[Category:Bisexual writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT memoirists]]\n[[Category:Bisexual men]]\n[[Category:LGBT pornographic film actors]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Grants Pass, Oregon]]\n[[Category:People from Cazenovia, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Pornographic film actors from Oregon]]\n[[Category:Writers from Oregon]]\n[[Category:LGBT poets]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Oregon]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Writers from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:20th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:Writers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:Radical Faeries]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Gay pornographic film actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox adult biography\n|name = Scott O'Hara\n|image = Scott OHara Advocate Men May 1985.jpg\n|image_size = 220px\n|caption = Scott O'Hara, circa 1984\n|birth_name = John Robert Scott\n|birth_date = {{birth date|mf=yes|1961|10|16}}\n|birth_place = [[Grants Pass, Oregon]], U.S.\n|spouse =\n|death_date = {{Death date and age|mf=yes|1998|02|18|1961|10|16}}\n|death_place = [[San Francisco, California]], U.S.\n|height = \n|weight =\n|alias = Spunk\n|films =\n|number of films =\n|website =\n}}\n\n'''Scott O'Hara''' (October 16, 1961 \u2013 February 18, 1998) was an American pornographic performer, author, poet, editor and publisher.  He rose to prominence during the mid-1980s for his work in such gay adult films as ''Winner Takes All'', ''Below The Belt'' and ''In Your Wildest Dreams''. O'Hara wrote four books: ''SeXplorers: The Guide to Doing It on the Road'', ''Do It Yourself Piston Polishing (for Non-Mechanics)'', ''Autopornography: A Memoir of Life in the Lust Lane'', and ''Rarely Pure and Never Simple: Selected Essays of Scott O'Hara'', and edited and published the quarterly men's sex journal ''[[Steam (gay magazine)|Steam]]'' and the cultural magazine ''Wilde''.\n\n==Acting career==\nO'Hara was born '''John Robert Scott''' on October 16, 1961 in [[Grants Pass, Oregon]], one of seven children of Robert Hogue Scott and Martha Jane (n\u00e9e Farwell) Scott. While the family lived modestly on the family farm, there was inherited wealth, and for much of his life Scott was supported by a trust fund. Scott was known professionally as \"Scott O'Hara\" or \"Spunk\"<ref name=\"Advocate Men\">{{citation|title='Spunk'. The name reverberates, the body arrests.|date=May 1985|work=Advocate Men}}</ref> and used his professional name throughout his adult life.  In an essay titled \"A Dick by Any Other Name\", O'Hara wrote: \"I knew from an early age that I was a changeling. I spent the next eighteen years looking for my real name, and since I found it I have not pretended to be anyone else.\"<ref name=\"Rarely Pure and never simple\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QKlE8exUdeMC&pg=PA5&lpg=PA5&dq=|title=A Dick by Any Other Name|author=Scott O'Hara|work=Rarely pure and never simple|publisher=Psychology Press. \u00a91999|isbn=9780789005731|year=1999}}</ref>\n\nHe first came to prominence when he was awarded the title \"The Man With The Biggest Dick in San Francisco\" in a contest in the early 1980s. That title became his trademark for the rest of his porn and professional career. Published measurement of his penis varies from 9.5 to 11&nbsp;inches. From 1983-88, he appeared in over twenty gay and bisexual-themed adult films and videos, several of which demonstrate his rare ability of [[autofellatio|auto-fellatio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gayeroticvideoindex.com/V/4/1404.html|title=Head Over Heels|date=1988|work=All Worlds Video}}</ref>  In addition to his work in adult films, O'Hara starred in ''Making Porn'', a play by [[Ronnie Larsen]] based on conversations by Larsen with Scott O'Hara. He described his work in porn as \"a sheer delight from the word go\".<ref name=\"Autopornography-p.90\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-H-ZS4J5oiAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Autopornography:+A+Memoir+of+Life+in+the+Lust+Lane#v=onepage&q=bisexual&f=false|title=Autopornography: A Memoir of Life in the Lust Lane|author=Scott O'Hara|date=1997|publisher=Haworth Press|isbn=9780789001443}}, p. 90.</ref>\n\n==Writing career==\nAfter he contracted HIV, offers to appear in porn ended. In 1991 he moved to [[Cazenovia, Wisconsin]] and started a new career as an author. He edited and published from 1993 to 1995 the quarterly men's journal ''Steam'', \"the intellectual review of public sex\", intended to facilitate [[Cruising for sex|cruising]]. According to its first issue, ''Steam'' focused on \"public and semi-public sex. Our purpose is to provide a sex-positive forum for subjects considered taboo by other mags. We are aware that many activities mentioned in these pages are illegal in many parts of the world, and we do not advocate unlawful activity\". In an advertisement in Volume 2, No. 1, he further stated that the publication was \"all about sex - all kinds of sex, but especially public, publicly-disapproved, exciting sex\". Articles often featured rest room, park, and other risky sexual encounters, and every issue contained tips on cruising spots (public places to meet men for sex), with notes on their safety or lack of same.<ref>Wisconsin GLBT History Project, http://www.mkelgbthist.org/media/print/steam.htm, consulted 10-29-2014.</ref>\n\nReturning to San Francisco in 1995, he published five issues of the short-lived cultural magazine ''Wilde''; he also contributed to a number of other publications. O'Hara wrote the four books  mentioned above. As a playwright, he contributed to the musical, ''Ex-Lovers'', which had a successful run at the [[Theatre Rhinoceros]] in San Francisco.<ref name=\"POZ\">{{cite web|url=http://www.poz.com/articles/228_7134.shtml|title=Full of Spunk|author=Adam Gillitt|date=June 1998|accessdate=January 14, 2014|work=Poz Magazine}}</ref>\n\nUpon his death, he left his personal papers (consisting of 39 boxes of journals, correspondence, notes, and manuscripts) to the [[John Hay Library]] of [[Brown University]]. The archives of the [[GLBT Historical Society]] in San Francisco preserve a collection of O'Hara's performance costumes and other memorabilia.<ref>Scott O'Hara Artifacts (collection no. 1998-19); see the entry in the [http://www.glbthistory.org/research online catalog of the society].</ref> The sibling to whom he had been closest was the lesbian activist and poet Claudia (Ann) Scott<ref>https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/37308382</ref><ref>''Sinister Wisdom'', No13 http://www.sinisterwisdom.org/sites/default/files/Sinister%20Wisdom%2013.pdf</ref> who left him the poem ''For My Youngest Brother''.<ref>''Lesbian Writer: Collected Work Of Claudia Scott'', Naiad Press 1981</ref>\n\n==Sexuality==\nO'Hara identified as gay.<ref name=\"Autopornography-p.114\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-H-ZS4J5oiAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Autopornography:+A+Memoir+of+Life+in+the+Lust+Lane#v=onepage&q=bisexual&f=false|title=Autopornography: A Memoir of Life in the Lust Lane|author=Scott O'Hara|date=1997|publisher=Haworth Press|isbn=9780789001443}}, p. 114</ref> He said he was \"obsessed with anything sexual\" as young as eleven,<ref name=\"Autopornography-p.70\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-H-ZS4J5oiAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Autopornography:+A+Memoir+of+Life+in+the+Lust+Lane#v=onepage&q=bisexual&f=false|title=Autopornography: A Memoir of Life in the Lust Lane|author=Scott O'Hara|date=1997|publisher=Haworth Press|isbn=9780789001443}}, p. 70</ref> and that his first sex with another man took place when he was fifteen, when he seduced, or perhaps raped (the word is his), a twenty-eight-year-old.<ref name=\"Autopornography-p.71\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-H-ZS4J5oiAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Autopornography:+A+Memoir+of+Life+in+the+Lust+Lane#v=onepage&q=bisexual&f=false|title=Autopornography: A Memoir of Life in the Lust Lane|author=Scott O'Hara|date=1997|publisher=Haworth Press|isbn=9780789001443}}, p. 71</ref> He called [[monogamy]] \"unnatural,\" and stated that \"having our [gay men's] mouth full of dick has been a political statement like no other\".<ref>\"Talking with My Mouth Full\", p. 81.</ref> He frequented [[gay bathhouses]] and other men's sex clubs, and much enjoyed sex in public parks. Until his HIV infection, he had \"a different man every night, or nearly\".<ref>''Autopornography'', p. 120.</ref>\n\nO'Hara was a proponent of [[barebacking]], praising the freedom from fear of risk it gave him. This attracted criticism both during his life, and following his death.<ref>e.g. See discussion between the notable authors Ricketts & Halsall, ''Gaynet List Serve'', Feb 1998: https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/bit.listserv.gaynet/U8GN3aqUGOk</ref> He called his HIV infection, which he believed he contracted in 1981, \"an undeniable blessing\",<ref name=\"Autopornography, p. 129\">''Autopornography'', p. 129</ref> and \"admired..tremendously\" two people who \"consciously made the decision to seroconvert\" (to contract HIV; see [[bugchasing]]).<ref name=\"Autopornography, p. 129\"/><ref>\"Talking with My Mouth Full\", p. 84.</ref> He had \"HIV+\" tattooed on his bicep in 1994, then tore the sleeves off many of his shirts so it would be visible.<ref>''Autopornography'', p. 128.?</ref><ref>[[David M. Halperin]], ''What Do Gay Men Want?'' pp. 88-89, University of Michigan Press, 2007</ref> Once he had progressed to AIDS, he talked about it \"at every available opportunity\".<ref>\"Talking with My Mouth Full\", p. 83.</ref> He wrote in detail about his treatment for lymphoma and the pain he endured.<ref>''Out On A Lymphoma'', ''POZ'', June 1998 http://www.poz.com/articles/228_1623.shtml</ref>\n\nO'Hara did not have, and did not want, a long-term relationship. He said that there were six times in his life when he was in love, deeply and thoroughly, for a period of a month or more.<ref>''Autopornography'', p. 159.</ref> \"The concept of 'Lover' (or 'Spouse', or 'Partner', or whatever) is basically, intrinsically antithetical to what my Philosophy of Life holds up as the ideal\".<ref>''Autopornography'', p. 173.</ref>\n\nO'Hara acted in multiple [[Bisexual pornography|bisexual films]] throughout his life, but did not identify as bisexual. However, he listed ''Switch Hitters 2'' as one of his favorite films, partly because he got to experience the novelty of sex with a woman, something he'd always wanted to do. He claimed to enjoy the scene and was proud of his butch appearance in the role, writing that \"in all my years of ass-pounding, I'd never once gotten into a pussy, and I felt as if this were a serious gap in my sexual education, which needed filling.\"<ref name=\"Autopornography-p.114\"/>\n\n==Death==\nHis trust fund exhausted, O'Hara spent his final years in a windowless San Francisco apartment he called \"The Cave\", surrounded by his record albums, CDs, books, and erotic art, and occupied his time gardening.<ref name=\"POZ\"/> He lived with [[HIV]] for more than 10 years and had developed [[non-Hodgkin lymphoma]] for almost five years.  He dubbed his illness \"The Death Spoor\", and died of [[AIDS]]-related complications in San Francisco on February 18, 1998, at age 36.<ref name=\"POZ\"/> He donated his collection of over 500 works of erotic art to The Tom of Finland Foundation.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldoftomoffinland.com/tomsblog/?p=4626 | title=Scott O'Hara \u2013 ToFF Lifetime Member &#124; TOM's Blog}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}} \n*''Winner Takes All'' (1982)\n*''California Blue'' (1983)\n*''Ramcharger'' (1984)\n*''Slaves for Sale 2'' (1984)\n*''The Joys of Self-Abuse'' (1985)\n*''The Other Side Of Aspen 2'' (1985)\n*''Sgt. Swann's Private Files'' (1985)\n*''Sighs'' (1985)\n*''Advocate Men Live! 1'' (1986)\n*''Below the Belt'' (1986)\n*''The Guy Next Door'' (1986)\n*''Hung and Horny'' (1986)\n*''Oversized Load'' (1986)\n*''Sex-Hunt'' (1986)\n*''Stick Shift'' (1986)\n*''In Your Wildest Dreams'' (1987)\n*''Switch Hitters 2'' (1987)\n*''Advocate Men Live! 4'' (1988)\n*''Double Standards'' (1988)\n*''Head Over Heels 1'' (1988)\n*''New Recruits'' (1988)\n*''The Sex Party'' (1992)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Publications==\n* \"How I Got AIDS. Memoirs of a Working Boy\", ''Diseased Pariah News'', No. 3, 1991, p.&nbsp;7; No. 4, 1991, pp.&nbsp;7\u20138 (pictured on p.&nbsp;2); No. 5, no date, p.&nbsp;6; No. 6, 1992, p.&nbsp;14; No. 7, 1992, p.&nbsp;29; https://web.archive.org/web/20160624103522/http://www.diseasedpariahnews.com/, retrieved 10-29-2014. \n*  ''SeXplorers: The Guide to Doing It on the Road'', San Francisco, PDA Press, 1995, {{ISBN|9780964548015}}.\n*  ''Do It Yourself Piston Polishing (for Non-Mechanics)'' (Badboy, 1996) {{ISBN|9781563334894}}.\n*  ''Autopornography: A Memoir of Life in the Lust Lane'' (New